                <h2><b>Our Story</b></h2>
                <p>In May 2014, Scientific American discovered that children of mothers with a lower education had <b>noisier, weaker</b> and <b>more variable</b> neural activity in response to sound and greater activity in the absence of sound. However, those who learned to play a musical instrument for at least four years exhibited <b>far faster neural responses</b> to speech even after four decades. In 2015, the Washington Post reported that <b>51% of children</b> fall under the reduced and free lunch qualifications, marking an explosion in the number of underprivileged youth. Despite music being one of the <b>most valuable developmental activities</b> for youth, more than half of them are unable to afford lessons.</p>
                <p>Seeking to solve this growing problem, our team designed and implemented Piano++, an <b>innovative, realtime</b> musical experience that allows anyone to instantly connect with music mentors from around the world to learn from the comfort of their own homes. Because our software is compatible with <b>any MIDI keyboard</b>, users of all backgrounds have the chance to flourish and develop their minds.</p>
